  "prompt": "Is it true that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is true that money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The purpose is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nLegal frameworks against money laundering are in place to combat organized crime, drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and other illegal activities. These laws require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement systems and controls to detect and report suspicious activities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe and may include large fines, seizure of assets, and imprisonment. The specific laws and penalties vary by country, but the illegality of money laundering is a global norm, reinforced by international agreements and organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).",
